Gxy Text-jiypJG HTML__Container-lweot jYDSem hNRlaL hYFQYa"><p><em>=E2=80=
=9CSculpture is the art of the hole and the lump.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94<a href=
=3D"https://www.artsy.net/artist/auguste-rodin">Auguste Rodin</a></em></p>
<p>From the Parthenon frieze and the Easter Island <em>maoi</em> to the Chi=
nese Terracotta Warriors and the prehistoric <em>Venus of Willendorf</em>, =
sculpture is a medium as diverse as it is ancient. Traditionally worked in =
natural materials like stone, clay, and metal, sculpture encompasses both f=
ree-standing works =E2=80=9Cin-the-round=E2=80=9D and reliefs, often servin=
g as architectural elements. Sharing the viewer=E2=80=99s space more litera=
lly than any other medium, sculpture has given rise to some of the most ico=
nic works in art history, including the classical Greek <em>Venus de Milo</=
em> (c. 130-100 B.C.), <a href=3D"https://www.artsy.net/artist/michelangelo=
-buonarroti">Michelangelo</a>=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://www.artsy.net/ge=
ne/high-renaissance">High Renaissance</a> <em>David</em> (1504), Rodin=E2=
=80=99s <em>The Thinker</em> (1902), and <a href=3D"https://www.artsy.net/a=
rtist/constantin-brancusi">Constantin Brancusi</a>=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.artsy.net/artwork/constantin-brancusi-the-kiss-le-baiser"><em>The =
Kiss</em></a> (1908). The 20th century saw the explosion of traditional scu=
lpture, wherein virtually any material=E2=80=94like <a href=3D"https://www.=
artsy.net/artist/john-chamberlain">John Chamberlain</a>=E2=80=99s car parts=
 or <a href=3D"https://www.artsy.net/artist/marcel-duchamp">Marcel Duchamp<=
/a>=E2=80=99s readymades=E2=80=94could be used, as well as the rise of such=
 diverse movements as <a href=3D"https://www.artsy.net/gene/kinetic-sculptu=
re">kinetic sculpture</a>, sound sculpture, environmental art, and <a href=
=3D"https://www.artsy.net/gene/minimalism">Minimalist</a> sculpture.</p>
